WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:05.115 --> 00:00:06.520
RETO MEIER: Good morning,
everyone.

00:00:06.520 --> 00:00:08.720
Welcome to Android Developers
Strike Back.

00:00:08.720 --> 00:00:11.360
Last week, we heartlessly
reviewed camera apps in the

00:00:11.360 --> 00:00:13.320
app clinic and redesigned
those apps in

00:00:13.320 --> 00:00:14.170
Android Design In Action.

00:00:14.170 --> 00:00:16.830
Now it's time for the developers
of those apps to

00:00:16.830 --> 00:00:17.210
have their say.

00:00:17.210 --> 00:00:18.100
My name is Reto Meier.

00:00:18.100 --> 00:00:19.570
IAN NI-LEWIS: And I'm
Ian Ni-Lewis.

00:00:19.570 --> 00:00:21.780
Today, we're lucky to be joined
by the developers of

00:00:21.780 --> 00:00:25.510
three of the apps we looked at
last week, including IM CTO

00:00:25.510 --> 00:00:29.530
Ramzi Risk, Glimmr developer
Paul Bourke, and Alex Drizen

00:00:29.530 --> 00:00:31.210
of Camera ZOOM FX.

00:00:31.210 --> 00:00:34.360
As always, we're safe in the
Android Developers bunker in

00:00:34.360 --> 00:00:35.870
an undisclosed location.

00:00:35.870 --> 00:00:37.630
So Ramzi, Paul, and
Alex are joining

00:00:37.630 --> 00:00:39.140
us via Google+ Hangouts.

00:00:39.140 --> 00:00:42.330
RETO MEIER: Also joining us is
are resident design guru,

00:00:42.330 --> 00:00:44.654
Roman Nurik, live
from New York.

00:00:44.654 --> 00:00:46.255
ROMAN NURIK: It's
Saturday night.

00:00:46.255 --> 00:00:48.100
Hey, guys.

00:00:48.100 --> 00:00:50.090
IAN NI-LEWIS: Before we meet the
developers, let's quickly

00:00:50.090 --> 00:00:51.920
review last week's
prescriptions.

00:00:51.920 --> 00:00:54.305
Reto, what makes a
great camera app?

00:00:54.305 --> 00:00:55.660
RETO MEIER: Well, we
went through each

00:00:55.660 --> 00:00:57.090
of these last week.

00:00:57.090 --> 00:00:59.820
And really I think what it
comes down to is having

00:00:59.820 --> 00:01:02.990
something which is really
compelling.

00:01:02.990 --> 00:01:04.540
It's a very visual medium
so you want

00:01:04.540 --> 00:01:06.250
everything to just work.

00:01:06.250 --> 00:01:08.590
So, first and foremost, you want
it to look great without

00:01:08.590 --> 00:01:10.010
contradicting the
design guide.

00:01:10.010 --> 00:01:12.070
IAN NI-LEWIS: And I think that
was something that we really

00:01:12.070 --> 00:01:15.440
wanted to emphasize
because cameras

00:01:15.440 --> 00:01:16.880
are an artistic medium.

00:01:16.880 --> 00:01:18.760
They deserve an artistic
user interface.

00:01:18.760 --> 00:01:20.840
They don't need to look
like an alarm

00:01:20.840 --> 00:01:23.280
clock or a text editor.

00:01:23.280 --> 00:01:27.990
But they need to not contradict
or change our

00:01:27.990 --> 00:01:30.320
design guidelines in a way
that might confuse users.

00:01:30.320 --> 00:01:30.790
RETO MEIER: Exactly.

00:01:30.790 --> 00:01:32.560
You want it to be something
which is a really rich

00:01:32.560 --> 00:01:33.860
experience, but not a confusing
experience.

00:01:33.860 --> 00:01:34.540
IAN NI-LEWIS: Right.

00:01:34.540 --> 00:01:35.500
RETO MEIER: I think that's
really the cake.

00:01:35.500 --> 00:01:38.080
We want to make sure that it
supports every image in the

00:01:38.080 --> 00:01:38.730
image gallery.

00:01:38.730 --> 00:01:40.980
So there's a lot of these apps
which are providing filters

00:01:40.980 --> 00:01:41.770
for photos.

00:01:41.770 --> 00:01:44.655
We want to make sure that it
works, even if the image that

00:01:44.655 --> 00:01:46.510
you happen to choose
is on Picasa or

00:01:46.510 --> 00:01:47.560
some other image provider.

00:01:47.560 --> 00:01:48.090
IAN NI-LEWIS: Sure.

00:01:48.090 --> 00:01:49.260
Flickr or whatever, yeah.

00:01:49.260 --> 00:01:50.450
RETO MEIER: Exactly.

00:01:50.450 --> 00:01:53.675
Hipster filters we mentioned,
some way to be able to browse

00:01:53.675 --> 00:01:56.250
a community of photography,
which I think really helps

00:01:56.250 --> 00:01:57.600
draw you in and understand
what the benefits are.

00:01:57.600 --> 00:01:59.150
IAN NI-LEWIS: Yeah, that was
something that I hadn't really

00:01:59.150 --> 00:01:59.640
thought about.

00:01:59.640 --> 00:02:02.910
But it is a really nice bonus
to help you feel like you're

00:02:02.910 --> 00:02:04.660
part of a larger community
and compare

00:02:04.660 --> 00:02:05.605
your photos with others.

00:02:05.605 --> 00:02:06.440
RETO MEIER: Absolutely.

00:02:06.440 --> 00:02:09.080
And the last point which I
wanted to mention was that it

00:02:09.080 --> 00:02:10.759
should work on devices
without cameras.

00:02:10.759 --> 00:02:13.270
So Nexus 7 devices, anything
like that, which may not have

00:02:13.270 --> 00:02:15.760
a back-facing camera, but it's
a really great device for

00:02:15.760 --> 00:02:17.650
looking at photos and enjoying
that community.

00:02:17.650 --> 00:02:20.970
IAN NI-LEWIS: Now, remember,
though, we ended up adding one

00:02:20.970 --> 00:02:23.290
thing at the end that we didn't
put on this slide.

00:02:23.290 --> 00:02:27.940
And that is that, at least as of
Jelly Bean, which is a much

00:02:27.940 --> 00:02:32.720
faster OS UI wise than previous
OSes from Android,

00:02:32.720 --> 00:02:34.430
you should be able
to have jank-free

00:02:34.430 --> 00:02:35.650
scrolling in your app.

00:02:35.650 --> 00:02:38.220
So as I'm browsing a large
number of images--

00:02:38.220 --> 00:02:40.680
now, of course, sometimes you're
going to see a blank or

00:02:40.680 --> 00:02:42.680
placeholder image as
that image comes

00:02:42.680 --> 00:02:43.480
down from the network.

00:02:43.480 --> 00:02:46.480
But if the image has been
loaded, you should be able to

00:02:46.480 --> 00:02:49.040
scroll up and down without
seeing any jank.

00:02:49.040 --> 00:02:51.420
And by jank, we mean just
frame rate drops, little

00:02:51.420 --> 00:02:53.260
pauses in the scrolling.

00:02:53.260 --> 00:02:55.480
Some of the apps did that
really, really well, better

00:02:55.480 --> 00:02:56.760
than our own apps, in fact.

00:02:56.760 --> 00:02:58.090
IAN NI-LEWIS: Which is
always impressive.

00:02:58.090 --> 00:03:00.300
So it was great to see that and
definitely something which

00:03:00.300 --> 00:03:02.600
we are going to be looking for
in pretty much all the apps

00:03:02.600 --> 00:03:03.640
we'll look at in the future.

00:03:03.640 --> 00:03:05.101
I think that's going to
be a big part of it.

00:03:05.101 --> 00:03:06.120
IAN NI-LEWIS: Absolutely.

00:03:06.120 --> 00:03:08.220
RETO MEIER: So let's
get started.

00:03:08.220 --> 00:03:09.265
Let's have a look at
each of the apps.

00:03:09.265 --> 00:03:12.620
So these are the apps that
we reviewed on Friday.

00:03:12.620 --> 00:03:16.190
EyeMe, Glimmr, Camera ZOOM FX,
and, what was the other?

00:03:16.190 --> 00:03:17.110
Picnik, I think.

00:03:17.110 --> 00:03:18.780
IAN NI-LEWIS: I think you
said EyeMe again.

00:03:18.780 --> 00:03:19.970
But it's really EyeEm.

00:03:19.970 --> 00:03:20.330
RETO MEIER: It's EyeEm.

00:03:20.330 --> 00:03:22.900
I don't know why I keep
saying EyeMe.

00:03:22.900 --> 00:03:24.390
We should ask Ramzi,
see if he's willing

00:03:24.390 --> 00:03:25.110
to change the name.

00:03:25.110 --> 00:03:26.490
It's going to make it
much easier for me.

00:03:26.490 --> 00:03:29.820
So, happily, we do have the
developers of three of these

00:03:29.820 --> 00:03:31.340
apps to speak to today.

00:03:31.340 --> 00:03:35.770
We are going to start with
Ramzi from EyeEm.

00:03:35.770 --> 00:03:39.100
So before we do kick over to
him, I just want to show you

00:03:39.100 --> 00:03:44.180
quickly on screen here what the
lab results were judging

00:03:44.180 --> 00:03:46.660
by the criteria which
we put forward.

00:03:46.660 --> 00:03:48.750
And I think the two big concerns
we had were the

00:03:48.750 --> 00:03:51.140
ability to support every the
image in the gallery.

00:03:51.140 --> 00:03:53.550
And I think we had a
couple of concerns

00:03:53.550 --> 00:03:54.410
about the design guide.

00:03:54.410 --> 00:03:55.620
And can you remember
what was the jank

00:03:55.620 --> 00:03:58.160
factor like on the EyeEm?

00:03:58.160 --> 00:03:59.450
IAN NI-LEWIS: I'm
sorry, I don't.

00:03:59.450 --> 00:04:01.386
RETO MEIER: I think
it was reasonable.

00:04:01.386 --> 00:04:03.196
But I don't think it
was the standout.

00:04:03.196 --> 00:04:08.450
So let's get Ramzi on and let
him speak for himself.

00:04:08.450 --> 00:04:11.980
So hi, Ramzi, can you spend a
little bit of time-- tell us a

00:04:11.980 --> 00:04:14.530
little bit about yourself, a
little bit about the app, just

00:04:14.530 --> 00:04:16.992
so the audience knows
who you are.

00:04:16.992 --> 00:04:20.170
RAMZI RIZK: Absolutely, first of
all, thanks for having us.

00:04:20.170 --> 00:04:22.209
And thanks for the review.

00:04:22.209 --> 00:04:26.380
We can rename it to EyeMe as
soon as you guys release

00:04:26.380 --> 00:04:28.121
support for Action Bar on--

00:04:28.121 --> 00:04:29.504
[LAUGHTER]

00:04:29.504 --> 00:04:32.590
RETO MEIER: That's
a fair call.

00:04:32.590 --> 00:04:34.160
RAMZI RIZK: No worries there.

00:04:34.160 --> 00:04:35.535
Yeah, so, I'm Ramzi.

00:04:35.535 --> 00:04:40.030
I'm one of the engineers behind
EyeEm and one of the

00:04:40.030 --> 00:04:42.500
four guys that founded
it originally.

00:04:42.500 --> 00:04:44.820
Not much to say about myself.

00:04:44.820 --> 00:04:48.060
I develop Android, among
other things.

00:04:48.060 --> 00:04:51.420
Recently, our team has grown
over the last few months.

00:04:51.420 --> 00:04:54.280
And now we have actually some
really awesome developers that

00:04:54.280 --> 00:04:56.360
are taking care of most of
the Android development.

00:04:56.360 --> 00:04:58.300
And that's why the app has
gotten so much better over the

00:04:58.300 --> 00:05:00.620
last couple months.

00:05:00.620 --> 00:05:04.150
But yeah, and EyeEm
itself is--

00:05:04.150 --> 00:05:05.810
well, you can say it's a
photo-sharing platform.

00:05:05.810 --> 00:05:07.920
But we like to think
of it as the next

00:05:07.920 --> 00:05:10.350
generation of photo discovery.

00:05:10.350 --> 00:05:13.690
So photo filters, hipster photo
filters are all awesome.

00:05:13.690 --> 00:05:16.180
But what we really like
are data centers.

00:05:16.180 --> 00:05:19.730
And what we think is that the
fact that you're taking photos

00:05:19.730 --> 00:05:22.980
with your mobile means you have
so much more information

00:05:22.980 --> 00:05:24.510
available to you that
you don't need to

00:05:24.510 --> 00:05:25.890
make the user enter.

00:05:25.890 --> 00:05:27.070
So you don't need
the hash tags.

00:05:27.070 --> 00:05:27.910
You don't need all of that.

00:05:27.910 --> 00:05:29.295
But you have the location
information.

00:05:29.295 --> 00:05:30.720
You know what sort of
location it is.

00:05:30.720 --> 00:05:33.010
And based on that, you can
always learn a little more and

00:05:33.010 --> 00:05:35.410
make better recommendations.

00:05:35.410 --> 00:05:37.540
And that's what we're
trying to do EyeEm.

00:05:37.540 --> 00:05:40.810
So the idea is whenever you take
a photo, you're telling

00:05:40.810 --> 00:05:42.340
us a little bit more
about what you

00:05:42.340 --> 00:05:43.890
like and how you live.

00:05:43.890 --> 00:05:46.890
And we use that, learn a little
more, and make better

00:05:46.890 --> 00:05:49.890
recommendations so that you're
always getting nicer content

00:05:49.890 --> 00:05:50.610
recommended to you.

00:05:50.610 --> 00:05:54.320
And you're always discovering
content independent of the

00:05:54.320 --> 00:05:55.490
social graph.

00:05:55.490 --> 00:05:57.870
So it's buzzwords, topical
graph, interest

00:05:57.870 --> 00:05:58.900
graph, all of that.

00:05:58.900 --> 00:06:00.000
And that's what we're
focusing on.

00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:01.000
RETO MEIER: Very nice.

00:06:01.000 --> 00:06:01.510
And that's, in fact--

00:06:01.510 --> 00:06:03.680
I think the key thing for me
when I was browsing through

00:06:03.680 --> 00:06:06.970
the app was being able follow
these little bread crumbs of

00:06:06.970 --> 00:06:08.700
links, Things that,
ooh, that's taken

00:06:08.700 --> 00:06:10.020
at the Android building.

00:06:10.020 --> 00:06:11.690
I would love to see how many
other photos there are.

00:06:11.690 --> 00:06:13.790
So that, for me, was
really compelling.

00:06:13.790 --> 00:06:14.470
IAN NI-LEWIS: Absolutely.

00:06:14.470 --> 00:06:16.905
It's a very, very interesting
service.

00:06:16.905 --> 00:06:20.542
RAMZI RIZK: And can I say
one more thing quickly?

00:06:20.542 --> 00:06:21.960
RETO MEIER: Please, yeah,
this is all about you.

00:06:21.960 --> 00:06:22.910
RAMZI RIZK: Awesome.

00:06:22.910 --> 00:06:26.060
First of all, again, I want to
apologize because the app

00:06:26.060 --> 00:06:27.799
crashed while you were demoing
it, while you were trying to

00:06:27.799 --> 00:06:29.110
take a photo.

00:06:29.110 --> 00:06:31.300
And this is a funny story,
because we had actually just

00:06:31.300 --> 00:06:34.730
released that update a couple
hours before the show.

00:06:34.730 --> 00:06:40.260
And we'd switched our location
detection stuff into the

00:06:40.260 --> 00:06:41.720
repository that you
have on Google

00:06:41.720 --> 00:06:46.160
Groups, the Protips location.

00:06:46.160 --> 00:06:47.580
So we were sort of
inspired by that.

00:06:47.580 --> 00:06:52.350
And we tested it, and it was all
OK, except in the case of

00:06:52.350 --> 00:06:55.400
latitudes that were
minus 120, 122.

00:06:55.400 --> 00:06:57.640
So basically--

00:06:57.640 --> 00:07:00.425
yeah, and thanks for reporting
it because otherwise we

00:07:00.425 --> 00:07:01.410
wouldn't have found that.

00:07:01.410 --> 00:07:02.370
IAN NI-LEWIS: You're
very welcome.

00:07:02.370 --> 00:07:04.451
RAMZI RIZK: It was pretty
cool of you.

00:07:04.451 --> 00:07:05.530
RETO MEIER: Oh that's great.

00:07:05.530 --> 00:07:06.440
That's really interesting.

00:07:06.440 --> 00:07:11.290
So Ian's playing with
the app right now.

00:07:11.290 --> 00:07:13.280
IAN NI-LEWIS: I like how
Googolplex is a tech

00:07:13.280 --> 00:07:14.240
startup near you.

00:07:14.240 --> 00:07:15.470
RETO MEIER: [CHUCKLES].

00:07:15.470 --> 00:07:16.810
IAN NI-LEWIS: Yeah, that's
how we roll.

00:07:16.810 --> 00:07:17.860
RETO MEIER: Absolutely.

00:07:17.860 --> 00:07:20.460
Well, I can see a lot of
duct tape in this room.

00:07:20.460 --> 00:07:21.550
IAN NI-LEWIS: Yeah,
there you go.

00:07:21.550 --> 00:07:23.450
So, yeah, I think the scrolling

00:07:23.450 --> 00:07:24.700
is definitely usable.

00:07:24.700 --> 00:07:27.390
But, as you said, it wasn't
the standout.

00:07:27.390 --> 00:07:30.580
There are apps that scroll
a lot better than this.

00:07:30.580 --> 00:07:32.210
But in general, the performance
is pretty good.

00:07:32.210 --> 00:07:36.560
And I really, really like the
way that you can see these

00:07:36.560 --> 00:07:41.650
different categories, although
some of them are a little bit

00:07:41.650 --> 00:07:42.280
mystifying.

00:07:42.280 --> 00:07:44.260
Like I don't know why that
pretty girl on the train

00:07:44.260 --> 00:07:46.420
tracks was labeled coffee.

